Researchers from 60 countries found that 32.5% of amphibian species are at risk due to climate change and pollution.
The Cairns Frog Hospital in Australia, lacking government funding, closed its doors after treating sick frogs for six years.
In Peru, a gold mine blockade highlighted tensions between rural communities and the mining industry.
Additionally, the smuggling of rare frogs into Belgium raised conservation concerns.
Globally, amphibians face extinction threats, with pollutants causing hermaphroditism and population declines.
These findings underscore the urgent need for environmental conservation efforts to protect these vital species.
